INSERT INTO `search_dataset` VALUES (3416,'node',' we must do more in higher ed and lb will for oregon s economy to thrive higher education must change that may sound surprising coming from a college president but many are starting to question the value of college education versus taxpayer and student dollars spent the questions are worth asking and smart colleges will respond with answers and action earlier this month 850 people graduated with 996 degrees and certificates from linnbenton community college i am confident they will improve both their own lives and the quality of life in our communities but a recent report card for higher education issued by the us chamber of commerce gave oregon community colleges an f for the amount of money spent per degree earned the measurements had their flaws the chamber used a model developed for fouryear universities that doesn t consider the number of students in nondegree programs such as adult basic education ged and community education many argue that the ipeds model is no longer an accurate measure even for fouryear universities however our own data are enough for us to know we re not earning an a lbcc s success rate is 34 percent 12 percent of our students earn degrees or certificates and another 22 percent transfer to fouryear colleges and universities we can and must do better to help more of our citizens finish what they start at lbcc the oregon education investment board s goals and achievement compacts are a good start they challenge the education system to ensure 40 percent of adults have a bachelor s degree 40 percent have a twoyear degree or jobready certificate and 20 percent have at least a high school diploma or the equivalent by 2025 that means lbcc must increase the number of people earning degrees or certificates from 850 to 1350 per year despite significant cuts in state funding over the past three years our first moves must be to do new and better things with the resources we have already we are discussi