INSERT INTO `search_dataset` VALUES (3449,'node',' at 52 she decided to become a college freshman cleveland ohio it was january 2010 and susie porter was ready to give up the economy had gotten so bad that regulars at her restaurant were coming in one day a week instead of three or four her 26yearold daughter had taken a fall and fractured her neck pick up your baby and you could end up paralyzed  her doctor told her that s why porter was standing in the steamy kitchen of the town fryer at the agora stirring pots of gumbo and red beans and rice with a 1yearold on her hip she was 52 and single had no health insurance and her 10yearold jeep was emptying her wallet faster than a thief if all that wasn t worrying her her daughter s health was what if ali didn t recover how could porter support her and her baby for years on the little money she was bringing in  this is insane  porter told herself i can t live like this i ve got to do something she has in a few weeks susie porter leaves for upstate new york to begin her junior year of college on a full scholarship room and board included at an ivy league research university cornell if you have a dream if you had a dream it s never too late to go for it porter says my god i m 54 years old and i m going off to college it all happened because a friend stopped by the restaurant as he did every morning and told her he was going back to school that he d gotten enough financial aid to make it work you can get grants and you can get loans and you ll be ok he told porter on that cold january morning 212 years ago i ll show you how porter sat down next to him right there in the restaurant with her granddaughter on her lap and applied to cleveland state university  her next piece of good fortune was getting an adviser who explained csu s partnership program with cuyahoga community college  which allowed porter to take less expensive tric courses that counted toward a csu degree porter jumped on that but even with the lower tuition she needed grants and loans to make it the first semester she enrolled in three online classes taking nine credit hours so she could continue to take care of her daughter and granddaughter and because she was nervous about starting college in her 50s it had been 34 years since i had been in high school she says and i was wondering if i could still learn she got straight a s and she kept at it choosing urban affairs as her major her grades were good enough to get her into the honors program as well as induction into phi theta kappa  the academic honor society for twoyear colleges she was accepted into the robert l lewis academy of scholars  too scholarship money started coming in after that then in september 2011 she opened the mailbox and pulled out a letter from cornell inviting her to apply to its school of industrial and labor relations it was a perfect fit she d always been interested in workers rights and social justice yeah right porter said when she d finished reading and she laughs a soft sweet laugh that hints at her texas and louisiana roots with her daughter healed and the restaurant closed she went ahead and called the admissions office just as the letter suggested the following month she made the 5 12hour drive to ithaca ny  to check out the campus she was sold it s huge porter says but even in its enormity it feels like you are just absolutely enveloped in this nurturing environment it feels like it just wraps itself around you in february she sent in her application weeks later on a friday night she looked down at her cellphone and saw she d missed a call she checked voicemail ian schachner the associate director for admissions for the school of industrial and labor relations wanted to talk to her this can t be good  porter thought you get the fat envelope in the mail when you re accepted and she fretted all weekend when she called back on monday schachner told her he didn t want her to wait for an answer any longer cornell wanted her when he hung up porter says i cried like a baby porter knew her acceptance meant she d get financial help too because of cornell s policy of providing scholarships to students who can t afford tuition room and board that letter came later the total value of the school s offer 56497 for just the first year schachner says porter is the kind of student cornell searches for we talk a lot about diversity in education and diversity is often spoken of as race or ethnicity he said in a telephone interview but it also means diversity in life experiences we love students who have been out there for a while people who can help the younger students realize hey this is actually what goes on in organizations this is how the world really works his message to other students forget about the barriers you think are there there s an enormous number of fears that they have i can t afford it they d never take me i wouldn t be able to do the work i don t have the support schachner says the only thing that matches the number of fears they have is the actual support that exists to help them and that support porter says is a gift she never would have received if not for the people who helped her along the way and if not for tric ian told me that he had rarely seen a transfer student come in with as many transferable credits as i had she says that really says a lot for tric and it means more students like her can get into schools like cornell porter says she s willing to help them do it she s offering advice now on the blog she just created  susiep54posterouscom  if you work hard there s money available to go to school she says she wants to alert older students to hurdles besides money that they need to dig up high school transcripts for example and find old immunization records it s funny how people put labels on people porter says thinking back to everyone who knew her as the fry lady the woman who deepfried twinkies and oreos along with her famous chicken and baseballsized servings of homemade macaroni and cheese at the town fryer restaurant she ran for years on superior avenue they can t get past people having more than one side to them what s even more interesting is that it s hard for people to realize that they have more than one side to themselves they think they re too old to go back to school not porter in august she ll be in classrooms filled with 20yearold college juniors and in two years she ll have her bachelor s degree and have figured out what she ll do next law school is not out of the question she says i ll be 56 and i ll be ready to take on the world  http blogclevelandcom metro 201207 susieporterwhoonceranthehtml the plain dealer  ',0);
